Email: support@boulder-challenge.com
Responsible body is the natural or legal person who, alone or in concert with others, decides on the purposes and means of processing personal data (such as names, email addresses or similar).
Revoke your consent to data processing
Many data processing operations are only possible with your express consent. You can revoke an existing consent at any time by calling the appropriate function within the Boulder Challenge App to delete your user account. The legality of the data processing carried out until the revocation remains unaffected by the revocation.
Complaints to the relevant regulatory authority
In the case of violations of data protection law, the person concerned has the right of appeal to the competent supervisory authority. The competent supervisory authority in matters of data protection law is the state data protection officer of the federal state in which our company is based.
Data portability right
You have the right to have data that we process on the basis of your consent or in fulfillment of a contract automatically, in itself or to a third party in a standard, machine-readable format. If you require the direct transfer of data to another person in charge, this will only be done as far as technically feasible.
SSL or TLS encryption
For security reasons and to protect the transmission of confidential content that you send to us as a service provider, the Boulder Challenge App uses an SSL or TLS encryption.
If SSL or TLS encryption is enabled, the data you submit to us can not be read by third parties.
Information, Blocking, Deletion
You have the right to free information on your stored personal data, their origin and recipient and the purpose of the data processing and, if necessary, a right to rectification, blocking or deletion of these data. For further questions about personal data, you can contact us at any time at the address given in the imprint.
Oppose promotional mail
The use of contact data published in the context of the imprint obligation for the purpose of sending unsolicited advertising and information materials is hereby rejected. The operators of the Boulder Challenge App expressly reserve the right to take legal action in the event of the unsolicited sending of advertising information, such as spam emails.
3. Data protection supervisor
Christian Fenzl
4. Data collection when using the Boulder Challenge App
Server log files
The provider of the Boulder Challenge App server services automatically collects and stores information in so-called server log files, which are automatically transmitted to us during a service request. These include:
- User language set
- Operating system used
- Referrer URL
- Host name of the accessing client
- Time of server request
- IP address
There is no merge of this data with other data sources.
The basis for data processing is Art. 6 Abs. 1 lit. f DSGVO, which allows the processing of data to fulfill a contract or pre-contractual measures.
Registration form and profile data
You must register for the use of the Boulder Challenge App to use the services offered. We only use the data entered for the purpose of using the respective offer or service. The mandatory information requested during registration must be given in full. Otherwise we will reject the registration.
For important changes, for example, in the scope of the offer or in case of technical changes, we use the email address given during registration to inform you in this way.
The processing of the data entered during registration takes place on the basis of your consent (Art. 6 Abs. 1 lit. a DSGVO). You can revoke your consent at any time. The deletion of your user account within the Boulder Challenge App is sufficient. The legality of the already completed data processing remains untouched by the revocation.
The data collected during registration will be stored by us as long as you are registered for the Boulder Challenge App and will be deleted afterwards. Legal retention periods remain unaffected.
Processing more data
We collect, process and use personal data only insofar as they are necessary for the establishment, content or modification of the legal relationship (inventory data). This is done on the basis of Art. 6 Abs. 1 lit. b DSGVO, which allows the processing of data for the performance of a contract or precontractual measures. We only collect, process and use personal data on the use of the Boulder Challenge App (usage data) insofar as this is necessary in order to enable or charge the user for the use of the service.
The collected customer data will be deleted after termination of the business relationship. Legal retention periods remain unaffected.
Submit contract for services and digital content
We transfer personal data to third parties only if this is necessary in the context of the contract.
A further transmission of the data does not take place or only if you have expressly consented to the transmission. A transfer of your data to third parties without explicit consent, such as for advertising purposes, does not occur.
The basis for data processing is Art. 6 Abs. 1 lit. b DSGVO, which allows the processing of data for the performance of a contract or precontractual measures.
5. Analysis Tools
For the collection of statistics, usage information and the update check on all platforms an anonymous ID, type, version and language of the device, the service life and crash logs are collected. This is done using the Microsoft Visual Studio App Center (
https://appcenter.ms
).
6. Plugins and tools
YouTube
In our website, which you will be redirected to when you call "Help" within the Boulder Challenge App, we integrate videos from YouTube. In addition, users can add links to YouTube videos within boulder comments. This is a video portal of YouTube LLC., 901 Cherry Ave., 94066 San Bruno, CA, USA, hereafter referred to as "YouTube."
YouTube is a subsidiary of Google LLC., Gordon House, Barrow Street, Dublin 4, Ireland, hereafter referred to as "Google."
By accessing pages that have integrated YouTube videos, data will be transmitted to YouTube, stored and evaluated.
If you have a YouTube account and you're signed in, that data will be associated with your personal YouTube account and the data stored in it.
What data Google collects and how it uses your data can be found at
https://www.google.com/intl/de/policies/privacy/
.
